  <COMMENT line1="1" col1="1" line2="1" col2="78" start="331" end="408">## Convenience function for computing QC metrics and adding to pData &amp; rowData</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="15" col1="1" line2="15" col2="23" start="4951" end="4973">#' Calculate QC metrics</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="16" col1="1" line2="16" col2="2" start="5281" end="5282">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="17" col1="1" line2="17" col2="80" start="5611" end="5690">#' @param object an SingleCellExperiment object containing expression values and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="18" col1="1" line2="18" col2="67" start="5941" end="6007">#' experimental information. Must have been appropriately prepared.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="19" col1="1" line2="19" col2="94" start="6271" end="6364">#' @param exprs_values character(1), indicating slot of the \code{assays} of the \code{object}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="20" col1="1" line2="20" col2="90" start="6601" end="6690">#' should be used to define expression? Valid options are "counts" [default; recommended],</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="21" col1="1" line2="21" col2="83" start="6931" end="7013">#' "tpm", "fpkm" and "logcounts", or anything else in the object added manually by </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="22" col1="1" line2="22" col2="12" start="7261" end="7272">#' the user.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="23" col1="1" line2="23" col2="71" start="7591" end="7661">#' @param feature_controls a named list containing one or more vectors </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="24" col1="1" line2="24" col2="77" start="7921" end="7997">#' (character vector of feature names, logical vector, or a numeric vector of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="25" col1="1" line2="25" col2="65" start="8251" end="8315">#' indices are all acceptable) used to identify feature controls </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="26" col1="1" line2="26" col2="65" start="8581" end="8645">#' (for example, ERCC spike-in genes, mitochondrial genes, etc). </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="27" col1="1" line2="27" col2="79" start="8911" end="8989">#' @param cell_controls a character vector of cell (sample) names, or a logical</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="28" col1="1" line2="28" col2="77" start="9241" end="9317">#' vector, or a numeric vector of indices used to identify cell controls (for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="29" col1="1" line2="29" col2="42" start="9571" end="9612">#' example, blank wells or bulk controls).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="30" col1="1" line2="30" col2="79" start="9901" end="9979">#' @param nmads numeric scalar giving the number of median absolute deviations </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="31" col1="1" line2="31" col2="80" start="10231" end="10310">#' to be used to flag potentially problematic cells based on total_counts (total</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="32" col1="1" line2="32" col2="80" start="10561" end="10640">#' number of counts for the cell, or library size) and total_features (number of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="33" col1="1" line2="33" col2="80" start="10891" end="10970">#' features with non-zero expression). For total_features, cells are flagged for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="34" col1="1" line2="34" col2="78" start="11221" end="11298">#' filtering only if total_features is \code{nmads} below the median. Default </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="35" col1="1" line2="35" col2="14" start="11551" end="11564">#' value is 5.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="36" col1="1" line2="36" col2="78" start="11881" end="11958">#' @param pct_feature_controls_threshold numeric scalar giving a threshold for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="37" col1="1" line2="37" col2="80" start="12211" end="12290">#' percentage of expression values accounted for by feature controls. Used as to</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="38" col1="1" line2="38" col2="78" start="12541" end="12618">#' flag cells that may be filtered based on high percentage of expression from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="39" col1="1" line2="39" col2="20" start="12871" end="12890">#' feature controls.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="40" col1="1" line2="40" col2="2" start="13201" end="13202">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="41" col1="1" line2="41" col2="80" start="13531" end="13610">#' @details Calculate useful quality control metrics to help with pre-processing</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="42" col1="1" line2="42" col2="77" start="13861" end="13937">#' of data and identification of potentially problematic features and cells. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="43" col1="1" line2="43" col2="3" start="14191" end="14193">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="44" col1="1" line2="44" col2="41" start="14521" end="14561">#' The following QC metrics are computed:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="45" col1="1" line2="45" col2="13" start="14851" end="14863">#' \describe{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="46" col1="1" line2="46" col2="76" start="15181" end="15256">#'  \item{total_counts:}{Total number of counts for the cell (aka ``library </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="47" col1="1" line2="47" col2="12" start="15511" end="15522">#'  size'')}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="48" col1="1" line2="48" col2="63" start="15841" end="15903">#'  \item{log10_total_counts:}{Total counts on the log10-scale}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="49" col1="1" line2="49" col2="78" start="16171" end="16248">#'  \item{total_features:}{The number of endogenous features (i.e. not control</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="50" col1="1" line2="50" col2="73" start="16501" end="16573">#'  features) for the cell that have expression above the detection limit</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="51" col1="1" line2="51" col2="39" start="16831" end="16869">#'   (default detection limit is zero)}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="52" col1="1" line2="52" col2="72" start="17161" end="17232">#'  \item{filter_on_depth:}{Would this cell be filtered out based on its</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="53" col1="1" line2="53" col2="78" start="17491" end="17568">#'  log10-depth being (by default) more than 5 median absolute deviations from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="54" col1="1" line2="54" col2="44" start="17821" end="17864">#'  the median log10-depth for the dataset?}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="55" col1="1" line2="55" col2="75" start="18151" end="18225">#'  \item{filter_on_coverage:}{Would this cell be filtered out based on its</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="56" col1="1" line2="56" col2="79" start="18481" end="18559">#'  coverage being (by default) more than 5 median absolute deviations from the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="57" col1="1" line2="57" col2="37" start="18811" end="18847">#'  median coverage for the dataset?}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="58" col1="1" line2="58" col2="77" start="19141" end="19217">#'  \item{filter_on_pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Should the cell be filtered</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="59" col1="1" line2="59" col2="78" start="19471" end="19548">#'  out on the basis of having a high percentage of counts assigned to control</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="60" col1="1" line2="60" col2="75" start="19801" end="19875">#'  features? Default threshold is 80 percent (i.e. cells with more than 80</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="61" col1="1" line2="61" col2="65" start="20131" end="20195">#'  percent of counts assigned to feature controls are flagged).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="62" col1="1" line2="62" col2="71" start="20461" end="20531">#'  \item{counts_feature_controls:}{Total number of counts for the cell</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="63" col1="1" line2="63" col2="80" start="20791" end="20870">#'  that come from (one or more sets of user-defined) control features. Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="64" col1="1" line2="64" col2="74" start="21121" end="21194">#'   to zero if no control features are indicated. If more than one set of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="65" col1="1" line2="65" col2="77" start="21451" end="21527">#'   feature controls are defined (for example, ERCC and MT genes are defined</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="66" col1="1" line2="66" col2="79" start="21781" end="21859">#'   as controls), then this metric is produced for all sets, plus the union of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="67" col1="1" line2="67" col2="38" start="22111" end="22148">#'   all sets (so here, we get columns</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="68" col1="1" line2="68" col2="41" start="22441" end="22481">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls_ERCC},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="69" col1="1" line2="69" col2="42" start="22771" end="22812">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls_MT} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="70" col1="1" line2="70" col2="38" start="23101" end="23138">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls}).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="71" col1="1" line2="71" col2="66" start="23431" end="23496">#'  \item{log10_counts_feature_controls:}{Just as above, the total</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="72" col1="1" line2="72" col2="77" start="23761" end="23837">#'   number of counts from feature controls, but on the log10-scale. Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="73" col1="1" line2="73" col2="77" start="24091" end="24167">#'   to zero (i.e.~log10(0 + 1), offset to avoid negative infinite values) if</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="74" col1="1" line2="74" col2="39" start="24421" end="24459">#'   no feature control are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="75" col1="1" line2="75" col2="62" start="24751" end="24812">#'  \item{pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Just as for the counts</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="76" col1="1" line2="76" col2="72" start="25081" end="25152">#'   described above, but expressed as a percentage of the total counts.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="77" col1="1" line2="77" col2="76" start="25411" end="25486">#'   Defined for all control sets and their union, just like the raw counts.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="78" col1="1" line2="78" col2="58" start="25741" end="25798">#'   Defaults to zero if no feature controls are defined.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="79" col1="1" line2="79" col2="68" start="26071" end="26138">#'  \item{filter_on_pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Would this cell be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="80" col1="1" line2="80" col2="73" start="26401" end="26473">#'   filtered out on the basis that the percentage of counts from feature</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="81" col1="1" line2="81" col2="79" start="26731" end="26809">#'   controls is higher than a defined threhold (default is 80\%)? Just as with</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="82" col1="1" line2="82" col2="73" start="27061" end="27133">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls}, this is defined for all control sets</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="83" col1="1" line2="83" col2="22" start="27391" end="27412">#'   and their union.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="84" col1="1" line2="84" col2="329" start="27721" end="28049">#'  \item{pct_counts_top_50_features:}{What percentage of the total counts is accounted for by the 50 highest-count features? Also computed for the top 100 and top 200 features, with the obvious changes to the column names. Note that the top ``X'' percentage will not be computed if the total number of genes is less than ``X''.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="85" col1="1" line2="85" col2="73" start="28051" end="28123">#'  \item{pct_dropout:}{Percentage of features that are not ``detectably </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="86" col1="1" line2="86" col2="75" start="28381" end="28455">#'  expressed'', i.e. have expression below the \code{lowerDetectionLimit} </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="87" col1="1" line2="87" col2="15" start="28711" end="28725">#'  threshold.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="88" col1="1" line2="88" col2="74" start="29041" end="29114">#'  \item{counts_endogenous_features:}{Total number of counts for the cell</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="89" col1="1" line2="89" col2="77" start="29371" end="29447">#'   that come from endogenous features (i.e. not control features). Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="90" col1="1" line2="90" col2="54" start="29701" end="29754">#'   to `depth` if no control features are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="91" col1="1" line2="91" col2="72" start="30031" end="30102">#'  \item{log10_counts_endogenous_features:}{Total number of counts from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="92" col1="1" line2="92" col2="74" start="30361" end="30434">#'   endogenous features on the log10-scale. Defaults to all counts if no </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="93" col1="1" line2="93" col2="37" start="30691" end="30727">#'   control features are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="94" col1="1" line2="94" col2="74" start="31021" end="31094">#'  \item{n_detected_feature_controls:}{Number of defined feature controls</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="95" col1="1" line2="95" col2="75" start="31351" end="31425">#'    that have expression greater than the threshold defined in the object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="96" col1="1" line2="96" col2="54" start="31681" end="31734">#'    (that is, they are ``detectably expressed''; see</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="97" col1="1" line2="97" col2="78" start="32011" end="32088">#'    \code{object@lowerDetectionLimit} to check the threshold). As with other</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="98" col1="1" line2="98" col2="76" start="32341" end="32416">#'    metrics for feature controls, defined for all sets of feature controls</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="99" col1="1" line2="99" col2="77" start="32671" end="32747">#'    (set names appended as above) and their union. So we might commonly get</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="100" col1="1" line2="100" col2="54" start="33001" end="33054">#'    columns \code{n_detected_feature_controls_ERCC},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="101" col1="1" line2="101" col2="47" start="33331" end="33377">#'    \code{n_detected_feature_controls_MT} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="102" col1="1" line2="102" col2="71" start="33661" end="33731">#'    \code{n_detected_feature_controls} (ERCC and MT genes detected).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="103" col1="1" line2="103" col2="75" start="33991" end="34065">#'  \item{is_cell_control:}{Has the cell been defined as a cell control? If</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="104" col1="1" line2="104" col2="77" start="34321" end="34397">#'    more than one set of cell controls are defined (for example, blanks and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="105" col1="1" line2="105" col2="80" start="34651" end="34730">#'    bulk libraries are defined as cell controls), then this metric is produced</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="106" col1="1" line2="106" col2="74" start="34981" end="35054">#'     for all sets, plus the union of all sets (so we could typically get</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="107" col1="1" line2="107" col2="44" start="35311" end="35354">#'     columns \code{is_cell_control_Blank},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="108" col1="1" line2="108" col2="74" start="35641" end="35714">#'     \code{is_cell_control_Bulk}, and \code{is_cell_control}, the latter</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="109" col1="1" line2="109" col2="58" start="35971" end="36028">#'     including both blanks and bulks as cell controls).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="110" col1="1" line2="110" col2="4" start="36301" end="36304">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="111" col1="1" line2="111" col2="76" start="36631" end="36706">#' These cell-level QC metrics are added as columns to the ``phenotypeData''</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="112" col1="1" line2="112" col2="94" start="36961" end="37054">#' slot of the \code{\link{SingleCellExperiment}} object so that they can be inspected and are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="113" col1="1" line2="113" col2="70" start="37291" end="37360">#' readily available for other functions to use. Furthermore, wherever</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="114" col1="1" line2="114" col2="72" start="37621" end="37692">#' ``counts'' appear in the above metrics, the same metrics will also be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="115" col1="1" line2="115" col2="78" start="37951" end="38028">#' computed for ``exprs'', ``tpm'' and ``fpkm'' values (if TPM and FPKM values</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="116" col1="1" line2="116" col2="84" start="38281" end="38364">#' are present in the \code{SingleCellExperiment} object), with the appropriate term</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="117" col1="1" line2="117" col2="79" start="38611" end="38689">#' replacing ``counts'' in the name. The following feature-level QC metrics are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="118" col1="1" line2="118" col2="17" start="38941" end="38957">#' also computed:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="119" col1="1" line2="119" col2="13" start="39271" end="39283">#' \describe{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="120" col1="1" line2="120" col2="70" start="39601" end="39670">#' \item{mean_exprs:}{The mean expression level of the  gene/feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="121" col1="1" line2="121" col2="76" start="39931" end="40006">#' \item{exprs_rank:}{The rank of the feature's mean expression level in the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="122" col1="1" line2="122" col2="9" start="40261" end="40269">#' cell.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="123" col1="1" line2="123" col2="79" start="40591" end="40669">#' \item{n_cells_counts:}{The number of cells for which the expression level of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="124" col1="1" line2="124" col2="79" start="40921" end="40999">#' the feature is above the detection limit (default detection limit is zero).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="125" col1="1" line2="125" col2="75" start="41251" end="41325">#' \item{total_feature_counts:}{The total number of counts assigned to that</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="126" col1="1" line2="126" col2="29" start="41581" end="41609">#' feature across all cells.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="127" col1="1" line2="127" col2="79" start="41911" end="41989">#' \item{log10_total_feature_counts:}{Total feature counts on the log10-scale.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="128" col1="1" line2="128" col2="79" start="42241" end="42319">#' \item{pct_total_counts:}{The percentage of all counts that are accounted for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="129" col1="1" line2="129" col2="42" start="42571" end="42612">#' by the counts assigned to the feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="130" col1="1" line2="130" col2="75" start="42901" end="42975">#' \item{pct_dropout:}{The percentage of all cells that have no detectable </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="131" col1="1" line2="131" col2="78" start="43231" end="43308">#' expression (i.e. \code{is_exprs(object)} is \code{FALSE}) for the feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="132" col1="1" line2="132" col2="74" start="43561" end="43634">#' \item{is_feature_control:}{Is the feature a control feature? Default is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="133" col1="1" line2="133" col2="76" start="43891" end="43966">#' `FALSE` unless control features are defined by the user. If more than one</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="134" col1="1" line2="134" col2="75" start="44221" end="44295">#' feature control set is defined (as above), then a column of this type is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="135" col1="1" line2="135" col2="79" start="44551" end="44629">#' produced for each control set (e.g. here, \code{is_feature_control_ERCC} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="136" col1="1" line2="136" col2="60" start="44881" end="44940">#' \code{is_feature_control_MT}) as well as the column named</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="137" col1="1" line2="137" col2="78" start="45211" end="45288">#' \code{is_feature_control}, which indicates if the feature belongs to any of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="138" col1="1" line2="138" col2="21" start="45541" end="45561">#' the control sets.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="139" col1="1" line2="139" col2="4" start="45871" end="45874">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="140" col1="1" line2="140" col2="77" start="46201" end="46277">#' These feature-level QC metrics are added as columns to the ``featureData''</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="141" col1="1" line2="141" col2="87" start="46531" end="46617">#' slot of the \code{SingleCellExperiment} object so that they can be inspected and are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="142" col1="1" line2="142" col2="80" start="46861" end="46940">#' readily available for other functions to use. As with the cell-level metrics,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="143" col1="1" line2="143" col2="74" start="47191" end="47264">#'  wherever ``counts'' appear in the above, the same metrics will also be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="144" col1="1" line2="144" col2="79" start="47521" end="47599">#'  computed for ``exprs'', ``tpm'' and ``fpkm'' values (if TPM and FPKM values</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="145" col1="1" line2="145" col2="85" start="47851" end="47935">#'  are present in the \code{SingleCellExperiment} object), with the appropriate term</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="146" col1="1" line2="146" col2="37" start="48181" end="48217">#'  replacing ``counts'' in the name.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="147" col1="1" line2="147" col2="2" start="48511" end="48512">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="148" col1="1" line2="148" col2="41" start="48841" end="48881">#' @return an SingleCellExperiment object</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="408" col1="1" line2="408" col2="53" start="134641" end="134693">#' Identify if a cell is an outlier based on a metric</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="409" col1="1" line2="409" col2="3" start="134971" end="134973">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="410" col1="1" line2="410" col2="65" start="135301" end="135365">#' @param metric numeric or integer vector of values for a metric</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="411" col1="1" line2="411" col2="77" start="135631" end="135707">#' @param nmads scalar, number of median-absolute-deviations away from median</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="412" col1="1" line2="412" col2="47" start="135961" end="136007">#' required for a value to be called an outlier</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="413" col1="1" line2="413" col2="76" start="136291" end="136366">#' @param type character scalar, choice indicate whether outliers should be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="414" col1="1" line2="414" col2="81" start="136621" end="136701">#' looked for at both tails (default: "both") or only at the lower end ("lower") </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="415" col1="1" line2="415" col2="31" start="136951" end="136981">#' or the higher end ("higher")</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="416" col1="1" line2="416" col2="77" start="137281" end="137357">#' @param log logical, should the values of the metric be transformed to the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="417" col1="1" line2="417" col2="80" start="137611" end="137690">#' log10 scale before computing median-absolute-deviation for outlier detection?</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="418" col1="1" line2="418" col2="77" start="137941" end="138017">#' @param subset logical or integer vector, which subset of values should be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="419" col1="1" line2="419" col2="73" start="138271" end="138343">#' used to calculate the median/MAD? If \code{NULL}, all values are used.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="420" col1="1" line2="420" col2="76" start="138601" end="138676">#' Missing values will trigger a warning and will be automatically ignored. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="421" col1="1" line2="421" col2="77" start="138931" end="139007">#' @param batch factor of length equal to \code{metric}, specifying the batch</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="422" col1="1" line2="422" col2="80" start="139261" end="139340">#' to which each observation belongs. A median/MAD is calculated for each batch,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="423" col1="1" line2="423" col2="54" start="139591" end="139644">#' and outliers are then identified within each batch.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="424" col1="1" line2="424" col2="77" start="139921" end="139997">#' @param min.diff numeric scalar indicating the minimum difference from the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="425" col1="1" line2="425" col2="79" start="140251" end="140329">#' median to consider as an outlier. The outlier threshold is defined from the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="426" col1="1" line2="426" col2="74" start="140581" end="140654">#' larger of \code{nmads} MADs and \code{min.diff}, to avoid calling many </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="427" col1="1" line2="427" col2="68" start="140911" end="140978">#' outliers when the MAD is very small. If \code{NA}, it is ignored.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="428" col1="1" line2="428" col2="3" start="141241" end="141243">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="429" col1="1" line2="429" col2="79" start="141571" end="141649">#' @description Convenience function to determine which values for a metric are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="430" col1="1" line2="430" col2="53" start="141901" end="141953">#' outliers based on median-absolute-deviation (MAD).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="431" col1="1" line2="431" col2="3" start="142231" end="142233">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="432" col1="1" line2="432" col2="76" start="142561" end="142636">#' @return a logical vector of the same length as the \code{metric} argument</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="433" col1="1" line2="433" col2="3" start="142891" end="142893">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="434" col1="1" line2="434" col2="10" start="143221" end="143230">#' @export</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="1118" col1="1" line2="1118" col2="58" start="368941" end="368998">### Plot expression frequency vs mean for feature controls</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1120" col1="1" line2="1120" col2="61" start="369601" end="369661">#' Plot frequency of expression against mean expression level</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1121" col1="1" line2="1121" col2="2" start="369931" end="369932">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1122" col1="1" line2="1122" col2="55" start="370261" end="370315">#' @param object an \code{SingleCellExperiment} object.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1123" col1="1" line2="1123" col2="78" start="370591" end="370668">#' @param feature_set character, numeric or logical vector indicating a set of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1124" col1="1" line2="1124" col2="57" start="370921" end="370977">#' features to plot. If character, entries must all be in</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1125" col1="1" line2="1125" col2="74" start="371251" end="371324">#' \code{rownames(object)}. If numeric, values are taken to be indices for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1126" col1="1" line2="1126" col2="80" start="371581" end="371660">#' features. If logical, vector is used to index features and should have length</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1127" col1="1" line2="1127" col2="76" start="371911" end="371986">#' equal to \code{nrow(object)}. If \code{NULL}, then the function checks if</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1128" col1="1" line2="1128" col2="79" start="372241" end="372319">#' feature controls are defined. If so, then only feature controls are plotted,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1129" col1="1" line2="1129" col2="41" start="372571" end="372611">#' if not, then all features are plotted.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1130" col1="1" line2="1130" col2="83" start="372901" end="372983">#' @param feature_controls character, numeric or logical vector indicating a set of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1131" col1="1" line2="1131" col2="74" start="373231" end="373304">#' features to be used as feature controls for computing technical dropout</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1132" col1="1" line2="1132" col2="76" start="373561" end="373636">#' effects. If character, entries must all be in \code{rownames(object)}. If</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1133" col1="1" line2="1133" col2="78" start="373891" end="373968">#' numeric, values are taken to be indices for features. If logical, vector is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1134" col1="1" line2="1134" col2="78" start="374221" end="374298">#' used to index features and should have length equal to \code{nrow(object)}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1135" col1="1" line2="1135" col2="79" start="374551" end="374629">#' If \code{NULL}, then the function checks if feature controls are defined. If</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1136" col1="1" line2="1136" col2="44" start="374881" end="374924">#' so, then these feature controls are used.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1137" col1="1" line2="1137" col2="71" start="375211" end="375281">#' @param shape (optional) numeric scalar to define the plotting shape.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1138" col1="1" line2="1138" col2="80" start="375541" end="375620">#' @param alpha (optional) numeric scalar (in the interval 0 to 1) to define the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1139" col1="1" line2="1139" col2="49" start="375871" end="375919">#'  alpha level (transparency) of plotted points.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1140" col1="1" line2="1140" col2="77" start="376201" end="376277">#' @param show_smooth logical, should a smoothed fit through feature controls</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="1148" col1="1" line2="1148" col2="2" start="378841" end="378842">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1149" col1="1" line2="1149" col2="69" start="379171" end="379239">#' @details This function plots gene expression frequency versus mean</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1150" col1="1" line2="1150" col2="75" start="379501" end="379575">#' expression level, which can be useful to assess the effects of technical</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1151" col1="1" line2="1151" col2="74" start="379831" end="379904">#' dropout in the dataset. We fit a non-linear least squares curve for the</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="1381" col1="1" line2="1381" col2="80" start="455731" end="455810">################################################################################</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1383" col1="1" line2="1383" col2="44" start="456391" end="456434">#' Plot a relative log expression (RLE) plot</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1384" col1="1" line2="1384" col2="2" start="456721" end="456722">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1385" col1="1" line2="1385" col2="82" start="457051" end="457132">#' Produce a relative log expression (RLE) plot of one or more transformations of </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1386" col1="1" line2="1386" col2="26" start="457381" end="457406">#' cell expression values.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1387" col1="1" line2="1387" col2="2" start="457711" end="457712">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1388" col1="1" line2="1388" col2="54" start="458041" end="458094">#' @param object an \code{SingleCellExperiment} object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1389" col1="1" line2="1389" col2="80" start="458371" end="458450">#' @param exprs_mats named list of expression matrices. Entries can either be a </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1390" col1="1" line2="1390" col2="79" start="458701" end="458779">#' character string, in which case the corresponding expression matrix will be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1391" col1="1" line2="1391" col2="91" start="459031" end="459121">#' extracted from the SingleCellExperiment \code{object}, or a matrix of expression values.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1392" col1="1" line2="1392" col2="84" start="459361" end="459444">#' @param exprs_logged logical vector of same length as \code{exprs_mats} indicating</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1393" col1="1" line2="1393" col2="82" start="459691" end="459772">#' whether the corresponding entry in \code{exprs_mats} contains logged expression</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1394" col1="1" line2="1394" col2="46" start="460021" end="460066">#' values (\code{TRUE}) or not (\code{FALSE}).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1395" col1="1" line2="1395" col2="85" start="460351" end="460435">#' @param colour_by character string defining the column of \code{colData(object)} to</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1396" col1="1" line2="1396" col2="81" start="460681" end="460761">#' be used as a factor by which to colour the points in the plot. Alternatively, </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1397" col1="1" line2="1397" col2="83" start="461011" end="461093">#' a data frame with one column, containing values to map to colours for all cells.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1398" col1="1" line2="1398" col2="81" start="461341" end="461421">#' @param style character(1), either \code{"minimal"} (default) or \code{"full"},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1399" col1="1" line2="1399" col2="84" start="461671" end="461754">#' defining the boxplot style to use. \code{"minimal"} uses Tufte-style boxplots and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1400" col1="1" line2="1400" col2="68" start="462001" end="462068">#' is fast for large numbers of cells. \code{"full"} uses the usual </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1401" col1="1" line2="1401" col2="80" start="462331" end="462410">#' \code{\link{ggplot2}} and is more detailed and flexible, but can take a long </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1402" col1="1" line2="1402" col2="35" start="462661" end="462695">#' time to plot for large datasets.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1403" col1="1" line2="1403" col2="77" start="462991" end="463067">#' @param legend character, specifying how the legend(s) be shown? Default is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1404" col1="1" line2="1404" col2="80" start="463321" end="463400">#' \code{"auto"}, which hides legends that have only one level and shows others.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1405" col1="1" line2="1405" col2="44" start="463651" end="463694">#' Alternative is "none" (hide all legends).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1406" col1="1" line2="1406" col2="76" start="463981" end="464056">#' @param order_by_colour logical, should cells be ordered (grouped) by the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1407" col1="1" line2="1407" col2="77" start="464311" end="464387">#' \code{colour_by} variable? Default is \code{TRUE}. Useful for visualising </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1408" col1="1" line2="1408" col2="58" start="464641" end="464698">#' differences between batches or experimental conditions.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1409" col1="1" line2="1409" col2="73" start="464971" end="465043">#' @param ncol integer, number of columns for the facetting of the plot. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1410" col1="1" line2="1410" col2="16" start="465301" end="465316">#' Default is 1.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1411" col1="1" line2="1411" col2="78" start="465631" end="465708">#' @param ... further arguments passed to \code{\link[ggplot2]{geom_boxplot}}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1412" col1="1" line2="1412" col2="2" start="465961" end="465962">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1413" col1="1" line2="1413" col2="31" start="466291" end="466321">#' @return a ggplot plot object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1414" col1="1" line2="1414" col2="2" start="466621" end="466622">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1415" col1="1" line2="1415" col2="12" start="466951" end="466962">#' @details </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1416" col1="1" line2="1416" col2="86" start="467281" end="467366">#' Unwanted variation can be highly problematic and so its detection is often crucial.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1417" col1="1" line2="1417" col2="80" start="467611" end="467690">#' Relative log expression (RLE) plots are a powerful tool for visualising such </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1418" col1="1" line2="1418" col2="76" start="467941" end="468016">#' variation in high dimensional data. RLE plots are particularly useful for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1419" col1="1" line2="1419" col2="78" start="468271" end="468348">#' assessing whether a procedure aimed at removing unwanted variation, i.e. a </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1420" col1="1" line2="1420" col2="79" start="468601" end="468679">#' normalisation procedure, has been successful. These plots, while originally </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1421" col1="1" line2="1421" col2="81" start="468931" end="469011">#' devised for gene expression data from microarrays, can also be used to reveal </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1422" col1="1" line2="1422" col2="82" start="469261" end="469342">#' unwanted variation in single-cell expression data, where such variation can be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1423" col1="1" line2="1423" col2="15" start="469591" end="469605">#' problematic.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1424" col1="1" line2="1424" col2="3" start="469921" end="469923">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1425" col1="1" line2="1425" col2="80" start="470251" end="470330">#' If style is "full", as usual with boxplots, the box shows the inter-quartile </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1426" col1="1" line2="1426" col2="80" start="470581" end="470660">#' range and whiskers extend no more than 1.5 * IQR from the hinge (the 25th or </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1427" col1="1" line2="1427" col2="82" start="470911" end="470992">#' 75th percentile). Data beyond the whiskers are called outliers and are plotted </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1428" col1="1" line2="1428" col2="72" start="471241" end="471312">#' individually. The median (50th percentile) is shown with a white bar.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1429" col1="1" line2="1429" col2="3" start="471571" end="471573">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1430" col1="1" line2="1430" col2="79" start="471901" end="471979">#' If style is "minimal", then median is shown with a circle, the IQR in a grey</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1431" col1="1" line2="1431" col2="81" start="472231" end="472311">#' line, and "whiskers" (as defined above) for the plots are shown with coloured </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1432" col1="1" line2="1432" col2="52" start="472561" end="472612">#' lines. No outliers are shown for this plot style.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1433" col1="1" line2="1433" col2="2" start="472891" end="472892">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1434" col1="1" line2="1434" col2="15" start="473221" end="473235">#' @references </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1435" col1="1" line2="1435" col2="94" start="473551" end="473644">#' Gandolfo LC, Speed TP. RLE Plots: Visualising Unwanted Variation in High Dimensional Data. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1436" col1="1" line2="1436" col2="68" start="473881" end="473948">#' arXiv [stat.ME]. 2017. Available: http://arxiv.org/abs/1704.03590</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1437" col1="1" line2="1437" col2="2" start="474211" end="474212">#'</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="1439" col1="1" line2="1439" col2="17" start="474871" end="474887">#' Davis McCarthy</COMMENT>
